docs.abstract: The Kentucky Republican is the first senator to be diagnosed with the novel coronavirus. He went about his routine for days after being tested, potentially exposing many colleagues.
docs.snippet: The Kentucky Republican is the first senator to be diagnosed with the novel coronavirus. He went about his routine for days after being tested, potentially exposing many colleagues.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senate Republicans were struggling to salvage a more than $1 trillion economic rescue package to respond to the coronavirus crisis when they got the message on Sunday afternoon: One of their own had been walking around the Capitol with Covid-19 for days as they debated how best to confront the rapidly spreading pandemic.

headline.main: Rand Paul Tests Positive for Covid-19, Fueling Anxiety in the Capitol

byline.original: By Nicholas Fandos and Catie Edmondson

docs.abstract: President Trump has delegated the authority to invoke extraordinary powers over private industry, but his administration does not seem to be using it yet.
docs.snippet: President Trump has delegated the authority to invoke extraordinary powers over private industry, but his administration does not seem to be using it yet.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump issued an executive order this week invoking the Defense Production Act to battle the coronavirus pandemic, but his advisers have resisted making aggressive use of the law to mobilize private industry.

headline.main: How the Defense Production Act Could Yield More Masks, Ventilators and Tests

docs.abstract: Government exercises, including one last year, made clear that the U.S. was not ready for a pandemic like the coronavirus. But little was done.
docs.snippet: Government exercises, including one last year, made clear that the U.S. was not ready for a pandemic like the coronavirus. But little was done.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The outbreak of the respiratory virus began in China and was quickly spread around the world by air travelers, who ran high fevers. In the United States, it was first detected in Chicago, and 47 days later, the World Health Organization declared a pandemic. By then it was too late: 110 million Americans were expected to become ill, leading to 7.7 million hospitalized and 586,000 dead.

headline.main: Before Virus Outbreak, a Cascade of Warnings Went Unheeded
headline.print_headline: Warning of a Pandemic Last Year Was Unheeded

keywords.name: organizations
keywords.value: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention

byline.original: By David E. Sanger, Eric Lipton, Eileen Sullivan and Michael Crowley

docs.abstract: Signs of a large-scale federal response to the coronavirus outbreak have begun to appear, generating praise from local officials but also pleas that they need much more.
docs.snippet: Signs of a large-scale federal response to the coronavirus outbreak have begun to appear, generating praise from local officials but also pleas that they need much more.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Federal emergency response teams toured a convention center in New York City on Monday, a sign that a much-needed temporary hospital is on the way. California has received hundreds of thousands of masks for those on the front lines of the outbreak. And President Trump said desperately needed protective equipment was on its way to Washington State.

headline.main: As Federal Government Mobilizes, Local Officials Say Response Remains Too Slow

byline.original: By Zolan Kanno-Youngs and Eric Lipton

docs.abstract: Hours after Democrats blocked the nearly $2 trillion package, a marathon set of private negotiations appeared to have yielded important compromises.
docs.snippet: Hours after Democrats blocked the nearly $2 trillion package, a marathon set of private negotiations appeared to have yielded important compromises.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Treasury secretary and the top Senate Democrat said late Monday that they were on the brink of a deal on a nearly $2 trillion emergency economic aid measure to respond to the coronavirus pandemic, after a marathon day of talks as Democrats demanded stronger protections for workers and restrictions for bailed-out businesses.

headline.main: Top Senate Democrat and Treasury Secretary Say They Are Near a Stimulus Deal
headline.print_headline: Rancor Makes Stimulus Bill A Heavy Lift

byline.original: By Emily Cochrane and Nicholas Fandos

docs.abstract: The United States, China and Europe are battling to be the first to find a cure, bringing a nationalist element to a worldwide crisis.
docs.snippet: The United States, China and Europe are battling to be the first to find a cure, bringing a nationalist element to a worldwide crisis.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A global arms race for a coronavirus vaccine is underway.

headline.main: Search for Coronavirus Vaccine Becomes a Global Competition
headline.print_headline: A Global Race To Figure Out A Silver Bullet

byline.original: By David E. Sanger, David D. Kirkpatrick, Sui-Lee Wee and Katrin Bennhold

docs.abstract: It remains unclear if the effort to enlist companies like General Motors, Apple and Hanes constitutes an effective strategy.
docs.snippet: It remains unclear if the effort to enlist companies like General Motors, Apple and Hanes constitutes an effective strategy.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s refusal to invoke the Defense Production Act to commandeer resources for the federal government is based on a bet that he can cajole the nation’s biggest manufacturers and tech firms to come together in a market-driven, if chaotic, consortium that will deliver critical equipment — from masks to ventilators — in time to abate a national crisis.

headline.main: Trump Bets Business Will Answer Call to Fight Virus, but Strategy Bewilders Firms
headline.print_headline: Trump Counts on Private Sector for Supplies

byline.original: By David E. Sanger, Ana Swanson and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: About 50 people gathered this month for a party in the upscale suburb of Westport, then scattered across the region and the world, taking the coronavirus with them.
docs.snippet: About 50 people gathered this month for a party in the upscale suburb of Westport, then scattered across the region and the world, taking the coronavirus with them.
docs.lead_paragraph: About 50 guests gathered on March 5 at a home in the stately suburb of Westport, Conn., to toast the hostess on her 40th birthday and greet old friends, including one visiting from South Africa. They shared reminiscences, a lavish buffet and, unknown to anyone, the coronavirus.

headline.main: Party Zero: How a Soirée in Connecticut Became a ‘Super Spreader’

byline.original: By Elizabeth Williamson and Kristin Hussey

docs.abstract: The Senate majority leader has encouraged judges thinking about stepping down to do so soon to ensure that Republicans confirm their replacements this year.
docs.snippet: The Senate majority leader has encouraged judges thinking about stepping down to do so soon to ensure that Republicans confirm their replacements this year.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Running out of federal court vacancies to fill, Senate Republicans have been quietly making overtures to sitting Republican-nominated judges who are eligible to retire to urge them to step aside so they can be replaced while the party still holds the Senate and the White House.

headline.main: McConnell Has a Request for Veteran Federal Judges: Please Quit
headline.print_headline: McConnell’s Pitch to Veteran Judges: Please Quit

docs.abstract: “It’s not racist at all,” the president said. But experts warned that the term could result in xenophobia.
docs.snippet: “It’s not racist at all,” the president said. But experts warned that the term could result in xenophobia.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Wednesday defended his increasingly frequent practice of calling the coronavirus the “Chinese Virus,” ignoring a growing chorus of criticism that it is racist and anti-Chinese.

headline.main: Trump Defends Using ‘Chinese Virus’ Label, Ignoring Growing Criticism
headline.print_headline: Trump Calls It the ‘Chinese Virus.’ Critics Say That’s Racist and Provocative.

byline.original: By Katie Rogers, Lara Jakes and Ana Swanson
